{
  "doc_id": "7672",
  "text": "Molecular control of GC initiation BCL-6. The upregulation of BCL-6 expression is essential for initiation of the GC reaction as BCL-6-deficient GC precursor B cells fail to enter the follicle [CITATION_1] . Of note, a particular region within the BCL-6 protein -repression domain 2 (RD2) -was found to be specifically required for the migration of GC precursor B cells towards the inner follicle [CITATION_2] . GC precursor B cells deficient for BCL-6 or with an inactivating mutation in the BCL-6 RD2 domain did not cease expression of G protein-coupled receptor 183 (GPR183; also known as EBI2) [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , which must be downregulated by GC precursor B cells to allow their migration towards the centre of the follicle [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . In addition, it was found that BCL-6-deficient GC precursor B cells did not upregulate expression of CXCR4 (REF. [CITATION_7] ), which is a chemokine receptor that is expressed by dark zone B cells in mice and humans [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . Also, Bcl6RD2 mut GC precursor B cells failed to downregulate expression of sphingosine-1-phosphate receptor type 1 (S1PR1) [CITATION_10] , which -in contrast to S1PR2, which promotes confinement of B cells in the GC [CITATION_11] -is minimally expressed by GC B cells [CITATION_12] ; this is consistent with the role of S1PR1 in mediating B cell trafficking out of the follicle [CITATION_13] . These findings indicate that in GC precursor B cells, BCL-6 controls a transcriptional programme that facilitates the migration of these cells to the centre of the follicle.",
